  {
    id: "concurrency-and-locks",
    category: "Technology",
    title: "Concurrency, Threads & Locks",
    tagline: "When two things happen at once and share a single memory, the obvious code is almost always subtly, intermittently, maddeningly wrong.",
    color: "#a3543f",
    glyph: "⇶",
    levels: [
      {
        depth: 1,
        title: "Ten Thousand Times Right, Once Wrong",
        body: `<p>For most of computing's history, a program was a story told one sentence at a time. The machine read a line, did the thing, moved to the next. You could follow it with your finger. If it worked when you tested it, it worked.</p><p>Then the machines grew many hands. A modern phone has eight cores; a server has dozens; and a program that keeps them all busy at once can run many times faster than one that politely waits its turn. This is the seduction. The terror arrives the moment two of those hands reach for the same thing — the same counter, the same list, the same single number in memory — at the same instant, and step on each other in a way no single line of code ever spelled out.</p><p>The horror story every working programmer eventually lives is this: a piece of code that runs correctly ten thousand times, passes every test, ships to a million users — and then, on the ten-thousand-and-first run, on someone else's machine, produces a number that is simply, quietly wrong. Not crashed. Not erroring. Just wrong, because two threads touched the same variable in an order you never imagined and the universe never promised to prevent.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 320" role="img" aria-label="A long run of program executions, each marked with a green check for a correct result. Run after run is right, ten thousand times over. Then, near the very end, one single run comes out wrong, marked in red, even though the code never changed."><style>.cl1 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.cl1-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.cl1-sub{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle }.cl1-axis{ stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.4 }.cl1-tick{ opacity:1; animation: cl1-rise .35s ease both }@keyframes cl1-rise{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateY(7px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateY(0)} }.cl1-ok{ stroke:#6b7d5c; stroke-width:2.4; fill:none; stroke-linecap:round }.cl1-bad{ stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2.8; fill:none; stroke-linecap:round }.cl1-badg{ animation: cl1-flash 1.1s ease both 2.0s }@keyframes cl1-flash{ 0%{opacity:0; transform:scale(.4)} 55%{opacity:1; transform:scale(1.25)} 100%{opacity:1; transform:scale(1)} transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center }.cl1-ring{ fill:none; stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:1.6; opacity:.85; animation: cl1-flash 1.1s ease both 2.05s }.cl1-lbl{ fill:#3d322a; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle }.cl1-redlbl{ fill:#a3543f; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600; animation: cl1-fade .5s ease both 2.5s }@keyframes cl1-fade{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.cl1-cap{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: cl1-fade .5s ease both 2.7s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .cl1 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="cl1"><text class="cl1-title" x="280" y="34">It worked. Until once it didn&#8217;t.</text><text class="cl1-sub" x="280" y="54">each box = one run of the same unchanged program</text><line class="cl1-axis" x1="40" y1="205" x2="520" y2="205"/><g transform="translate(60,150)"><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:.2s"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:.32s" transform="translate(38,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:.44s" transform="translate(76,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:.56s" transform="translate(114,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:.68s" transform="translate(152,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:.8s" transform="translate(190,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:.92s" transform="translate(228,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:1.04s" transform="translate(266,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:1.16s" transform="translate(304,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:1.28s" transform="translate(342,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:1.4s" transform="translate(380,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g><g class="cl1-badg" transform="translate(418,0)"><circle class="cl1-ring" cx="0" cy="0" r="15"/><path class="cl1-bad" d="M-7 -7 l14 14 M7 -7 l-14 14"/></g><g class="cl1-tick" style="animation-delay:1.55s" transform="translate(456,0)"><path class="cl1-ok" d="M-5 8 l4 6 l8 -14"/></g></g><text class="cl1-lbl" x="60" y="230">run 1</text><text class="cl1-lbl" x="288" y="230">&#183;&#183;&#183;</text><text class="cl1-lbl" x="440" y="230">run 10,001</text><text class="cl1-redlbl" x="478" y="190">wrong &#8594;</text><text class="cl1-cap" x="280" y="285">Not a crash. A silently wrong number &#8212; because two threads</text><text class="cl1-cap" x="280" y="303">touched the same memory in an order no line of code spelled out.</text></g></svg><figcaption>The same unchanged program runs correctly ten thousand times, then on the <b>ten-thousand-and-first</b> run quietly produces a wrong answer &#8212; the signature horror of concurrency.</figcaption></figure>`,
        pullQuote: "It worked ten thousand times. The terror is the ten-thousand-and-first."
      },
      {
        depth: 2,
        title: "Racing for the Same Memory",
        body: `<p>First, a distinction that people blur but shouldn't. <strong>Concurrency</strong> is a way of structuring a program so that many tasks are <em>in progress</em> at once — interleaved, taking turns, conceptually overlapping. <strong>Parallelism</strong> is when those tasks literally execute at the same instant on different hardware. You can have concurrency on a single core (the system rapidly switches between tasks) and you can have parallelism without much logical concurrency (one big calculation split across cores). Most hard problems live where the two meet.</p><p>The unit of concurrent execution is usually the <strong>thread</strong>: an independent sequence of instructions that runs within a program. Crucially, threads of the same program share the same memory — the same variables, the same data structures. That sharing is what makes them fast (no copying, instant communication) and what makes them dangerous.</p><p>The signature danger is the <strong>race condition</strong>: a situation where the correctness of the result depends on the precise <em>timing</em> of the threads — timing that the program does not control and cannot predict. The operating system may pause one thread between any two instructions and let another run. If both are modifying the same data, the outcome becomes a coin flip the program never meant to toss.</p><p>The fix is <strong>synchronization</strong>: arranging for only one thread at a time to enter the <strong>critical section</strong> — the stretch of code that touches the shared thing. This is <em>mutual exclusion</em>. The basic tool is the <strong>lock</strong>, or <strong>mutex</strong> (for <em>mutual exclusion</em>): a token only one thread can hold at once. Acquire it before the critical section, release it after, and the threads file through one at a time. But the lock births new monsters. <strong>Deadlock</strong>: two threads each holding a lock the other needs, waiting forever. <strong>Contention</strong>: so many threads queuing for one lock that the parallelism you paid for evaporates.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 360" role="img" aria-label="Two threads both want to enter a critical section that touches one shared memory cell. Without a lock they collide and the result is a coin-flip. A mutex is a token only one thread can hold at once: one thread acquires it and enters, the other waits at the gate, so they file through one at a time."><style>.cl2 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.cl2-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.cl2-h{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl2-th{ animation: cl2-in .5s ease both }.cl2-tA{ animation-delay:.25s } .cl2-tB{ animation-delay:.4s }@keyframes cl2-in{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateX(-8px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateX(0)} }.cl2-box{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:1.6 }.cl2-lbl{ fill:#3d322a; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle }.cl2-run{ animation-delay:.4s } .cl2-wait .cl2-box{ fill:#d8cdb8 }.cl2-arrow{ stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.8; fill:none; marker-end:url(#cl2a) }.cl2-aA{ animation: cl2-draw .5s ease both .7s } .cl2-aB{ animation: cl2-draw .5s ease both 1.5s }@keyframes cl2-draw{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.cl2-gate{ fill:#f4ede0; stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:2 }.cl2-lock{ fill:#b8923a; stroke:#1a1410; stroke-width:1.4 }.cl2-locktxt{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:11px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl2-crit{ fill:none; stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:1.8; stroke-dasharray:5 4 }.cl2-mem{ animation: cl2-pop .5s ease both 1.0s }@keyframes cl2-pop{ from{opacity:0; transform:scale(.6)} to{opacity:1; transform:scale(1)} transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center }.cl2-memc{ fill:#2c3447; stroke:#1a1410; stroke-width:1.6 }.cl2-memt{ fill:#f4ede0; font-size:13px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl2-wlbl{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: cl2-draw .5s ease both 1.7s }.cl2-okl{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: cl2-draw .5s ease both 1.3s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .cl2 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="cl2"><text class="cl2-title" x="280" y="34">A lock lets threads file through one at a time</text><text class="cl2-h" x="110" y="66">two threads</text><g class="cl2-th cl2-tA"><rect class="cl2-box" x="55" y="86" width="110" height="40" rx="6"/><text class="cl2-lbl" x="110" y="111">Thread A</text></g><g class="cl2-th cl2-tB cl2-wait"><rect class="cl2-box" x="55" y="196" width="110" height="40" rx="6"/><text class="cl2-lbl" x="110" y="221">Thread B</text></g><path class="cl2-arrow cl2-aA" d="M165 106 H 250"/><path class="cl2-arrow cl2-aB" d="M165 216 C 210 216 215 150 250 138"/><rect class="cl2-gate" x="250" y="96" width="40" height="52" rx="4"/><rect class="cl2-lock" x="258" y="112" width="24" height="20" rx="3"/><path d="M263 112 v-5 a7 7 0 0 1 14 0 v5" fill="none" stroke="#1a1410" stroke-width="1.4"/><text class="cl2-locktxt" x="270" y="166">mutex</text><rect class="cl2-crit" x="310" y="84" width="170" height="78" rx="8"/><text class="cl2-h" x="395" y="104">critical section</text><g class="cl2-mem"><rect class="cl2-memc" x="352" y="114" width="86" height="34" rx="5"/><text class="cl2-memt" x="395" y="136">shared x</text></g><text class="cl2-okl" x="230" y="86">A holds the lock &#8594; enters</text><text class="cl2-wlbl" x="205" y="255">B waits at the gate &#8594; no collision</text><text class="cl2-h" x="280" y="305" style="fill:#a3543f">the locks&#8217; new monsters</text><text class="cl2-lbl" x="148" y="332" style="text-anchor:start"><tspan style="fill:#a3543f;font-weight:600">Deadlock</tspan> &#8212; each waits on the other forever</text><text class="cl2-lbl" x="148" y="350" style="text-anchor:start"><tspan style="fill:#a3543f;font-weight:600">Contention</tspan> &#8212; the queue eats your parallelism</text><defs><marker id="cl2a" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L6 3 L0 6 Z" fill="#6b5d50"/></marker></defs></g></svg><figcaption>Only one thread holds the <b>mutex</b> at a time, so threads enter the <b>critical section</b> in single file &#8212; but the lock breeds new perils: deadlock and contention.</figcaption></figure>`,
        pullQuote: "Correctness should never depend on timing the program does not control."
      },
      {
        depth: 3,
        title: "Why x = x + 1 Is Three Steps",
        body: `<p>Consider the most innocent line in programming: <code>x = x + 1</code>. It looks atomic — indivisible — but the hardware sees three separate operations. <em>Read</em> the current value of <code>x</code> from memory into a register. <em>Modify</em> it by adding one. <em>Write</em> the result back to memory. Between any two of these steps, another thread may run.</p><p>Now let two threads each run <code>x = x + 1</code>, starting from <code>x = 0</code>. Thread A reads 0. Before A writes, Thread B reads 0 too. A computes 1 and writes 1. B computes 1 and writes 1. Two increments happened; <code>x</code> is 1, not 2. An increment was simply lost. This is the <strong>lost update</strong>, the canonical race, and it is invisible in the source code. The cure is to make the read-modify-write <em>atomic</em> — to guarantee no other thread can interleave — which is exactly what a lock provides.</p><p>The theory of these primitives was largely founded by <strong>Edsger Dijkstra</strong>. In 1965 he introduced the <strong>semaphore</strong>: an integer counter with two atomic operations, traditionally called <em>P</em> (wait — decrement, blocking if the count would go negative) and <em>V</em> (signal — increment, possibly waking a waiter). A semaphore initialized to 1 is a mutex; initialized to N, it allows N threads through at once. Semaphores can count resources, not just guard a door.</p><p>But a lock only lets you exclude; it does not let you <em>wait for a condition</em>. For that, C. A. R. Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed the <strong>monitor</strong> in the early 1970s, bundling shared data with the procedures that touch it, plus <strong>condition variables</strong> on which a thread can sleep until another thread signals that some state has changed (a queue is no longer empty, a buffer is no longer full).</p><p>Dijkstra also gave us the parable that haunts the field: the <strong>Dining Philosophers</strong>. Five philosophers sit around a table, a single fork between each pair. To eat, a philosopher needs both neighboring forks. If every philosopher grabs the fork on their left at the same moment, each holds one fork and waits forever for the right — perfect, symmetric <strong>deadlock</strong>. In 1971, Edward Coffman characterized the four conditions all of which must hold for deadlock: <em>mutual exclusion</em>, <em>hold-and-wait</em>, <em>no preemption</em>, and <em>circular wait</em>. Break any one and deadlock becomes impossible. The most common cure breaks the circular wait by imposing a global <strong>lock ordering</strong>: number the forks, and require everyone to pick up the lower-numbered fork first. One philosopher reaches for the same fork as their neighbor, loses, and the cycle never closes.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 380" role="img" aria-label="The single line x equals x plus one is really three hardware steps: read, modify, write. A timeline shows Thread A reading 0, then Thread B reading 0 before A has written, both computing 1, both writing 1. Two increments happened yet x ends at 1, not 2. One update was silently lost."><style>.cl3 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.cl3-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.cl3-mono{ font-family: ui-monospace, Menlo, monospace }.cl3-sub{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle }.cl3-axis{ stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.4; marker-end:url(#cl3a) }.cl3-laneL{ fill:#3d322a; font-size:12.5px; font-weight:600 }.cl3-step{ animation: cl3-in .4s ease both }.cl3-boxA{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:1.6 }.cl3-boxB{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#2c3447; stroke-width:1.6 }.cl3-st{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle }@keyframes cl3-in{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateY(6px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateY(0)} }.cl3-s1{ animation-delay:.3s } .cl3-s2{ animation-delay:.9s } .cl3-s3{ animation-delay:1.5s } .cl3-s4{ animation-delay:2.1s } .cl3-s5{ animation-delay:2.7s } .cl3-s6{ animation-delay:3.3s }.cl3-val{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:11px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic }.cl3-res{ animation: cl3-flash .8s ease both 4.0s }@keyframes cl3-flash{ from{opacity:0; transform:scale(.7)} to{opacity:1; transform:scale(1)} transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center }.cl3-resc{ fill:#fbeee6; stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:2 }.cl3-rest{ fill:#a3543f; font-size:14px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl3-lost{ fill:#a3543f; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: cl3-fade .5s ease both 4.5s }@keyframes cl3-fade{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .cl3 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="cl3"><text class="cl3-title cl3-mono" x="280" y="34">x = x + 1&#8194;<tspan class="cl3-sub" style="font-weight:400">is read &#183; modify &#183; write</tspan></text><text class="cl3-sub" x="280" y="56">both threads start from x = 0; time flows right &#8594;</text><line class="cl3-axis" x1="110" y1="96" x2="512" y2="96"/><text class="cl3-laneL" x="30" y="140">Thread A</text><text class="cl3-laneL" x="30" y="230">Thread B</text><line x1="100" y1="112" x2="100" y2="260" stroke="#d8cdb8" stroke-width="1.4"/><g class="cl3-step cl3-s1"><rect class="cl3-boxA" x="118" y="120" width="86" height="34" rx="5"/><text class="cl3-st" x="161" y="141">read x = 0</text></g><g class="cl3-step cl3-s2"><rect class="cl3-boxB" x="218" y="210" width="86" height="34" rx="5"/><text class="cl3-st" x="261" y="231">read x = 0</text></g><g class="cl3-step cl3-s3"><rect class="cl3-boxA" x="218" y="120" width="86" height="34" rx="5"/><text class="cl3-st" x="261" y="141">0+1 = 1</text></g><g class="cl3-step cl3-s4"><rect class="cl3-boxA" x="318" y="120" width="96" height="34" rx="5"/><text class="cl3-st" x="366" y="141">write x = 1</text></g><g class="cl3-step cl3-s5"><rect class="cl3-boxB" x="318" y="210" width="86" height="34" rx="5"/><text class="cl3-st" x="361" y="231">0+1 = 1</text></g><g class="cl3-step cl3-s6"><rect class="cl3-boxB" x="418" y="210" width="96" height="34" rx="5"/><text class="cl3-st" x="466" y="231">write x = 1</text></g><g class="cl3-res"><rect class="cl3-resc" x="360" y="288" width="160" height="44" rx="8"/><text class="cl3-rest" x="440" y="308">x = 1</text><text class="cl3-rest" x="440" y="326" style="font-size:11.5px;font-weight:400">two adds, one survives</text></g><text class="cl3-lost" x="195" y="305">expected x = 2.</text><text class="cl3-lost" x="195" y="323">An increment was lost.</text><defs><marker id="cl3a" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L6 3 L0 6 Z" fill="#6b5d50"/></marker></defs></g></svg><figcaption>Because read&#8211;modify&#8211;write is interruptible, B reads <b>x = 0</b> before A writes; both store 1, and one increment vanishes. This <b>lost update</b> is invisible in the source &#8212; a lock makes the trio atomic.</figcaption></figure>`
      },
      {
        depth: 4,
        title: "What One Thread Can See of Another",
        body: `<p>Beneath the mechanics of locks lies a subtler stratum that catches even experienced programmers: the <strong>memory model</strong>. The naive picture is that there is one memory, threads write to it and read from it, and a write by one thread is instantly visible to all others in the order it was issued. Every part of that picture is false on real hardware.</p><p>Modern CPUs and optimizing compilers <strong>reorder operations</strong>. The compiler may hoist a read out of a loop; the processor may execute instructions out of order, buffer writes in a store queue, and let a later read complete before an earlier write reaches memory. For a single thread this is invisible and harmless — the hardware preserves the illusion of sequential execution for code that doesn't share. But across threads, the reorderings leak. Thread A sets a <code>data</code> field and then a <code>ready</code> flag; Thread B sees <code>ready</code> become true but reads stale <code>data</code>, because the two writes reached memory in the opposite order.</p><p>The strongest, most intuitive guarantee is <strong>sequential consistency</strong>, defined by Leslie Lamport in 1979: the result of any execution is as if all operations were executed in <em>some</em> single total order, and each thread's operations appear in that order in the sequence it issued them. It is what we instinctively assume — and almost no real hardware provides it by default, because it is too expensive. Instead processors offer <strong>relaxed memory models</strong>, and the programmer must explicitly insert <strong>memory barriers</strong> (or <em>fences</em>): instructions that forbid certain reorderings, forcing prior writes to become visible before later operations proceed. Locks and atomics insert these barriers for you, which is the deeper reason they work: they don't merely exclude, they <em>publish</em>.</p><p>Why is sequential consistency "too expensive"? Because enforcing it would require every memory operation to become globally ordered, and that means draining or disabling the per-core <strong>store buffer</strong> — the small queue that lets a write retire into the pipeline while it trickles out to memory in the background — and forbidding the speculative, out-of-order execution that hides DRAM latency. A round trip to main memory costs on the order of 100 nanoseconds, while the register pipeline advances in well under a nanosecond; the store buffer exists precisely to keep the core busy across that ~100&times; gap. Under strict SC the core would have to stall on essentially every shared write rather than buffer it, often a 10&ndash;100&times; slowdown on synchronization-heavy code. That is why vendors ship relaxed models plus optional fences: you pay the ordering cost only where you actually need it.</p><p>The framework for reasoning about all this is the <strong>happens-before</strong> relation, also from Lamport's 1978 work on logical clocks. If event A happens-before event B — because they're in the same thread in order, or because A released a lock that B then acquired — then A's memory effects are guaranteed visible to B. If two accesses to the same location are <em>not</em> ordered by happens-before, and at least one is a write, you have a <strong>data race</strong>, and the result is undefined.</p><p>Two further axes organize the whole field. The first is the kind of <strong>progress</strong> guaranteed. <em>Blocking</em> algorithms use locks: a thread that stalls while holding a lock can stall everyone. <em>Non-blocking</em> (lock-free) algorithms guarantee that the system as a whole makes progress even if individual threads are delayed. The second axis is the kind of <strong>property</strong> you want to prove. <em>Safety</em> properties say "nothing bad ever happens" (no two threads in the critical section). <em>Liveness</em> properties say "something good eventually happens" (every waiting thread eventually proceeds; no deadlock, no starvation). The hardest truth of the discipline follows from all of this: because the failures depend on timings that occur rarely and unpredictably, <em>you cannot test concurrent code into correctness</em>. A test that passes proves the bug didn't fire this time. Correctness must be reasoned about, not sampled.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 360" role="img" aria-label="Thread A writes data then sets a ready flag, but a store buffer lets the two writes reach memory in the opposite order. Thread B sees ready become true yet reads stale data. A release-acquire pair establishes a happens-before edge that publishes A's writes to B before B proceeds, fixing the race."><style>.cl4 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.cl4-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.cl4-mono{ font-family: ui-monospace, Menlo, monospace; font-size:11.5px }.cl4-h{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl4-bad{ fill:#a3543f; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl4-ok{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl4-panel{ fill:none; stroke:#d8cdb8; stroke-width:1.4 }.cl4-tw{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:1.4 }.cl4-mt{ fill:#1a1410; text-anchor:middle }.cl4-step{ animation: cl4-in .45s ease both }@keyframes cl4-in{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateY(5px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateY(0)} }.cl4-d1{ animation-delay:.3s } .cl4-d2{ animation-delay:.65s } .cl4-d3{ animation-delay:1.0s } .cl4-d4{ animation-delay:1.35s } .cl4-d5{ animation-delay:2.0s } .cl4-d6{ animation-delay:2.35s } .cl4-d7{ animation-delay:2.7s }.cl4-flow{ stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:1.8; fill:none; marker-end:url(#cl4a) }.cl4-flowg{ stroke:#6b7d5c; stroke-width:2; fill:none; marker-end:url(#cl4b) }.cl4-note{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:11px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic }.cl4-hb{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .cl4 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="cl4"><text class="cl4-title" x="280" y="32">Reordering leaks across threads</text><rect class="cl4-panel" x="24" y="50" width="258" height="288" rx="8"/><rect class="cl4-panel" x="294" y="50" width="242" height="288" rx="8"/><text class="cl4-bad" x="153" y="70">data race &#8212; no ordering</text><text class="cl4-ok" x="415" y="70">release / acquire fence</text><g class="cl4-step cl4-d1"><rect class="cl4-tw" x="44" y="86" width="96" height="30" rx="4"/><text class="cl4-mt cl4-mono" x="92" y="105">data = 42</text></g><g class="cl4-step cl4-d2"><rect class="cl4-tw" x="44" y="124" width="96" height="30" rx="4"/><text class="cl4-mt cl4-mono" x="92" y="143">ready = 1</text></g><text class="cl4-h" x="92" y="176" style="font-size:11px">store buffer reorders</text><path class="cl4-flow cl4-step cl4-d3" d="M140 139 C 175 139 175 200 162 214"/><path class="cl4-flow cl4-step cl4-d3" d="M140 101 C 200 101 205 240 192 252"/><g class="cl4-step cl4-d4"><rect class="cl4-tw" x="152" y="204" width="110" height="30" rx="4" style="stroke:#2c3447"/><text class="cl4-mt cl4-mono" x="207" y="223">sees ready=1</text></g><g class="cl4-step cl4-d4"><rect class="cl4-tw" x="152" y="246" width="110" height="30" rx="4" style="stroke:#a3543f"/><text class="cl4-mt cl4-mono" x="207" y="265" style="fill:#a3543f">reads data=0</text></g><text class="cl4-note" x="153" y="300">B trusted the flag but got</text><text class="cl4-bad" x="153" y="318" style="font-size:12px">stale data &#8212; undefined</text><g class="cl4-step cl4-d5"><rect class="cl4-tw" x="314" y="86" width="100" height="30" rx="4"/><text class="cl4-mt cl4-mono" x="364" y="105">data = 42</text></g><g class="cl4-step cl4-d6"><rect class="cl4-tw" x="314" y="124" width="168" height="30" rx="4" style="stroke:#6b7d5c"/><text class="cl4-mt cl4-mono" x="398" y="143">store-release ready</text></g><path class="cl4-flowg cl4-step cl4-d7" d="M364 158 V 200"/><text class="cl4-hb cl4-step cl4-d7" x="446" y="183">happens&#8209;before</text><g class="cl4-step cl4-d7"><rect class="cl4-tw" x="314" y="206" width="168" height="30" rx="4" style="stroke:#6b7d5c"/><text class="cl4-mt cl4-mono" x="398" y="225">load-acquire ready=1</text></g><g class="cl4-step cl4-d7"><rect class="cl4-tw" x="314" y="244" width="100" height="30" rx="4"/><text class="cl4-mt cl4-mono" x="364" y="263">data = 42</text></g><text class="cl4-ok cl4-step cl4-d7" x="415" y="300" style="font-size:12px">writes published</text><text class="cl4-note cl4-step cl4-d7" x="415" y="318">B is guaranteed to see them</text><defs><marker id="cl4a" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L6 3 L0 6 Z" fill="#a3543f"/></marker><marker id="cl4b" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L6 3 L0 6 Z" fill="#6b7d5c"/></marker></defs></g></svg><figcaption>Without ordering, B sees the <b>ready</b> flag yet reads <b>stale data</b> &#8212; a data race. A release/acquire pair forges a <b>happens-before</b> edge that publishes A&#8217;s writes before B proceeds.</figcaption></figure>`,
        pullQuote: "A passing test proves only that the bug did not fire this time."
      },
      {
        depth: 5,
        title: "Compare-and-Swap and the Architecture of Lock-Free",
        body: `<p>At the bottom of every lock is a hardware primitive that does the impossible-seeming thing: a read and a write that the processor guarantees to perform <em>atomically</em>, with no interleaving. The workhorse is <strong>compare-and-swap</strong> (CAS). In pseudocode it behaves as if executed in a single indivisible step:</p><pre>CAS(addr, expected, new):
    if *addr == expected:
        *addr = new
        return true       // success
    else:
        return false      // someone else changed it</pre><p>CAS lets a thread say: "Update this location to <code>new</code>, but only if it still holds the value I last saw." If another thread snuck in, the CAS fails and you retry. From this single instruction you can build mutexes, semaphores, and — more ambitiously — data structures that need no locks at all. Here is a lock-free counter that never blocks:</p><pre>increment(counter):
    loop:
        old = atomic_load(counter)
        new = old + 1
        if CAS(counter, old, new):
            return new
        // else another thread won the race; loop and retry</pre><p>No thread can be stuck holding a lock, because there is no lock; the worst case is a few wasted retries under contention. This is the appeal of <strong>lock-free programming</strong>. But it hides a famous trap: the <strong>ABA problem</strong>. A thread reads value <code>A</code>, gets preempted; other threads change the location to <code>B</code> and then back to <code>A</code>. Our thread's CAS sees <code>A</code>, concludes nothing changed, and succeeds — even though the world moved underneath it (a node it intends to reuse may already have been freed). The classic defenses are tagged pointers with a version counter (so the value is really <code>(A, 7)</code> vs <code>(A, 9)</code>) and safe-reclamation schemes like hazard pointers or epoch-based reclamation.</p><p>It is worth being precise about what "never blocks" buys you, because the CAS counter above is <strong>lock-free</strong> but not <strong>wait-free</strong> &mdash; a distinction Maurice Herlihy made rigorous in his 1991 paper <em>Wait-Free Synchronization</em>. Lock-free means the <em>system</em> always advances: on every round of the race, whichever thread's CAS succeeds completes its operation, so the counter keeps climbing and no lock can stall everyone. But an individual unlucky thread can lose the CAS again and again, retrying without bound while others win &mdash; it never blocks, yet it may starve. Wait-freedom is the stronger guarantee that <em>every</em> thread finishes its operation within a fixed number of steps, no matter how fierce the contention. That bound is far harder to engineer, usually demanding helping schemes where threads finish one another's work.</p><p>Lock-free code also collides with the physical reality of caches. Memory is shared in <strong>cache lines</strong> of (typically) 64 bytes. When one core writes to a line, every other core's copy is invalidated and must be refetched — the cache-coherence protocol fires. <strong>Cache-line contention</strong> is the silent tax on hot shared variables. Worse is <strong>false sharing</strong>: two threads update two <em>different</em> variables that happen to sit on the <em>same</em> cache line, and the hardware ping-pongs the line between cores as if they were contending, even though logically they never touch the same data. Padding variables apart to separate lines can yield order-of-magnitude speedups.</p><p>The toolbox has finer instruments than the plain mutex. A <strong>reader-writer lock</strong> permits many concurrent readers but exclusive writers, ideal for read-heavy data. A <strong>spinlock</strong> busy-waits in a tight loop rather than sleeping — worthwhile only when the wait is expected to be shorter than the cost of a context switch; otherwise a <em>sleeping</em> lock that yields the CPU is far kinder.</p><p>The most durable escape, though, is to stop sharing mutable memory at all. <strong>Communicating Sequential Processes</strong> (Tony Hoare, 1978) models concurrency as independent processes that exchange messages over channels — "do not communicate by sharing memory; share memory by communicating," as the Go language motto distills it, with its goroutines and channels. The <strong>actor model</strong> (Carl Hewitt, 1973; later Erlang) gives each actor private state and a mailbox: actors only send each other messages, so there is no shared state to race over. <strong>Software transactional memory</strong> lets you mark a block as a transaction that either commits atomically or retries, borrowing the optimism of databases. And <strong>async/await</strong>, now in many languages, expresses concurrency as cooperatively scheduled tasks that voluntarily yield at <code>await</code> points — sidestepping preemptive races within a single thread, though not the deeper hazards once true parallelism returns.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 380" role="img" aria-label="A lock-free increment loop built on compare-and-swap. The thread loads the old value, computes new equals old plus one, then calls CAS. If the location still holds the old value the swap succeeds and the loop exits; if another thread changed it, CAS fails and the thread loops to retry. No lock is ever held."><style>.cl5 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.cl5-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.cl5-mono{ font-family: ui-monospace, Menlo, monospace }.cl5-sub{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle }.cl5-node{ animation: cl5-in .45s ease both }@keyframes cl5-in{ from{opacity:0; transform:scale(.85)} to{opacity:1; transform:scale(1)} transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center }.cl5-n1{ animation-delay:.3s } .cl5-n2{ animation-delay:.6s } .cl5-n3{ animation-delay:.9s } .cl5-n4{ animation-delay:1.7s } .cl5-n5{ animation-delay:1.3s }.cl5-box{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:1.6 }.cl5-cas{ fill:#fbf2e6; stroke:#b8923a; stroke-width:2 }.cl5-bt{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle }.cl5-arrow{ stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.8; fill:none; marker-end:url(#cl5a); animation: cl5-fade .4s ease both }.cl5-aok{ stroke:#6b7d5c; marker-end:url(#cl5b) }.cl5-aretry{ stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:1.8; fill:none; marker-end:url(#cl5c); stroke-dasharray:5 4 }.cl5-e1{ animation-delay:.5s } .cl5-e2{ animation-delay:.8s } .cl5-e3{ animation-delay:1.15s } .cl5-eok{ animation-delay:1.55s } .cl5-eretry{ animation-delay:1.9s }@keyframes cl5-fade{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.cl5-lbl{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:12px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.cl5-lblr{ fill:#a3543f; font-size:12px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.cl5-cap{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: cl5-fade .5s ease both 2.2s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .cl5 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="cl5"><text class="cl5-title" x="280" y="34">Compare-and-swap: a lock-free counter</text><text class="cl5-sub" x="280" y="54">no lock is ever held &#8212; the worst case is a wasted retry</text><g class="cl5-node cl5-n1"><rect class="cl5-box" x="180" y="78" width="200" height="38" rx="6"/><text class="cl5-bt cl5-mono" x="280" y="102">old = load(counter)</text></g><path class="cl5-arrow cl5-e1" d="M280 116 V 138"/><g class="cl5-node cl5-n2"><rect class="cl5-box" x="180" y="140" width="200" height="38" rx="6"/><text class="cl5-bt cl5-mono" x="280" y="164">new = old + 1</text></g><path class="cl5-arrow cl5-e2" d="M280 178 V 200"/><g class="cl5-node cl5-n3"><rect class="cl5-cas" x="150" y="202" width="260" height="56" rx="8"/><text class="cl5-bt cl5-mono" x="280" y="226" style="font-weight:600">CAS(counter, old, new)</text><text class="cl5-bt" x="280" y="246" style="font-size:11px;fill:#6b5d50">atomic: swap only if still == old</text></g><path class="cl5-arrow cl5-aok cl5-eok" d="M280 258 V 296"/><text class="cl5-lbl cl5-node cl5-eok" x="312" y="282">success</text><g class="cl5-node cl5-n4"><rect class="cl5-box" x="196" y="298" width="168" height="38" rx="6" style="stroke:#6b7d5c"/><text class="cl5-bt cl5-mono" x="280" y="322">return new</text></g><path class="cl5-aretry cl5-eretry" d="M410 230 C 470 230 470 97 382 97"/><text class="cl5-lblr cl5-node cl5-eretry" x="492" y="165">fail:</text><text class="cl5-lblr cl5-node cl5-eretry" x="490" y="182">retry</text><text class="cl5-cap" x="280" y="360">If another thread won the race, CAS returns false &#8212; loop and try again.</text><defs><marker id="cl5a" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L6 3 L0 6 Z" fill="#6b5d50"/></marker><marker id="cl5b" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L6 3 L0 6 Z" fill="#6b7d5c"/></marker><marker id="cl5c" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L6 3 L0 6 Z" fill="#a3543f"/></marker></defs></g></svg><figcaption>The thread reads <b>old</b>, computes <b>new</b>, and asks <b>CAS</b> to swap only if the value is unchanged. Success returns; a lost race simply loops &#8212; lock-free progress with no lock to stall on.</figcaption></figure>`
      },
      {
        depth: 6,
        title: "Formalizing the Unobservable",
        body: `<p>For decades, what a multithreaded program was even <em>allowed</em> to do was folklore. The watershed was the formalization of <strong>memory models</strong> as part of language specifications. The <strong>Java memory model</strong>, revised under JSR-133 (2004, with Jeremy Manson, William Pugh, and Sarita Adve central to the effort), and the <strong>C++11 memory model</strong> (shaped by Hans Boehm, Lawrence Crowl, and others) were hard-won achievements: they defined precisely, in terms of the happens-before relation and a hierarchy of atomic operations (<code>relaxed</code>, <code>acquire</code>, <code>release</code>, <code>seq_cst</code>), what reorderings a compiler and CPU may perform and what a correctly synchronized program may observe. A pivotal decision in both: a program containing a <strong>data race</strong> has <em>undefined behavior</em>. Not "an unpredictable value" — undefined, meaning the compiler is licensed to assume races never happen and optimize accordingly. The contract is stark: synchronize properly, or forfeit all guarantees.</p><p>A memory model says what is visible, but not what it <em>means</em> for a concurrent object to be correct. That gold standard came from Maurice Herlihy and Jeannette Wing in 1990: <strong>linearizability</strong>. Each operation must appear to take effect instantaneously at a single point between its invocation and its return, so the object behaves exactly like its sequential specification &#8212; it is what lets us reason about a lock-free queue as if it were an ordinary one. And why does <strong>compare-and-swap</strong> sit beneath every lock-free structure? Herlihy's 1991 <em>Wait-Free Synchronization</em> ranks each primitive by its <em>consensus number</em>: the most threads that can use it to agree, wait-free, on one value. Atomic read/write has consensus number one; CAS has consensus number infinity &#8212; it is <strong>universal</strong>, able to build any wait-free object, which is precisely why nothing weaker anchors the edifice.</p><p>These models had to confront the brute fact of <strong>weak memory hardware</strong>. The x86 architecture is relatively strong (it provides total-store-order, reordering only later reads ahead of earlier writes). <strong>ARM</strong> and IBM's Power are far weaker, freely reordering both reads and writes, so code that runs correctly on an Intel laptop can break on a phone. Researchers including Peter Sewell's group at Cambridge built rigorous mathematical and executable models of the actual ARM and x86 architectures — turning vendor prose into machine-checkable semantics, and uncovering bugs in the specifications themselves.</p><p>If testing cannot establish correctness, what can? <strong>Formal verification.</strong> Leslie Lamport — whose work on logical clocks, sequential consistency, and the Bakery algorithm anchors the field, and who received the 2013 Turing Award — created <strong>TLA+</strong>, a specification language in which one writes the system as a formula and a <strong>model checker</strong> exhaustively explores every possible interleaving, hunting for a state that violates a safety or liveness property. Amazon Web Services famously used TLA+ to find subtle bugs in production distributed protocols before deployment. Model checking and its relatives (SPIN, and the partial-order-reduction techniques that tame the combinatorial explosion of interleavings) are how serious concurrent algorithms are now validated.</p><p>On the pragmatic frontier, <strong>dynamic race detectors</strong> watch real executions: <strong>ThreadSanitizer</strong> (Konstantin Serebryany and colleagues at Google) instruments memory accesses and maintains happens-before information to flag races even when they don't manifest as wrong answers, becoming a routine part of large C++ and Go codebases. New hardware keeps changing the terrain too: <strong>transactional memory</strong> shipped in silicon (Intel's TSX), with mixed fortunes, and <strong>persistent memory</strong> raises the disorienting question of crash-consistency — which writes survived a power loss, and in what order — a memory-model problem aimed at durability rather than visibility.</p><p>The open problems are alive and humbling. Designing <strong>scalable lock-free and wait-free data structures</strong> that don't buckle under contention on hundred-core machines remains an art at the edge of research. <strong>Automatic detection of concurrency bugs</strong> — deadlocks, atomicity violations, and order violations — is far from solved; races slip past even instrumented tests because they require a specific schedule to fire. And the deepest design challenge is <strong>composability</strong>: two concurrent abstractions, each correct in isolation, routinely deadlock or race when combined, because locks and memory effects do not compose the way functions do. We can build a correct concurrent queue and a correct concurrent map; building a system that uses both, safely, may require reasoning about their interaction from scratch. Dijkstra gave us the primitives, Hoare gave us the structures and the message-passing alternative, Lamport gave us the logic to reason about time without a clock — and a century into computing, getting two things to happen at once, over one shared memory, correctly, remains one of the genuinely hard things we know how to do only with great care.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 384" role="img" aria-label="A spectrum of hardware memory models from strong to weak: x86 with total store order is relatively strong, while ARM and Power reorder freely and are weak, so code that runs on a laptop can break on a phone. Below, a model checker explores a branching tree of every possible interleaving to find a state that violates a safety property, because testing cannot."><style>.cl6 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.cl6-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.cl6-mono{ font-family: ui-monospace, Menlo, monospace }.cl6-h{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl6-bar{ animation: cl6-grow .8s ease both .3s }@keyframes cl6-grow{ from{transform:scaleX(0)} to{transform:scaleX(1)} transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:left }.cl6-axis{ stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.4 }.cl6-tk{ fill:#3d322a; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle }.cl6-chip{ animation: cl6-pop .5s ease both }.cl6-c1{ animation-delay:.6s } .cl6-c2{ animation-delay:.85s } .cl6-c3{ animation-delay:1.1s }@keyframes cl6-pop{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateY(5px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateY(0)} }.cl6-chipr{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:1.4 }.cl6-chipt{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.cl6-chips{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:10.5px; text-anchor:middle }.cl6-edge{ stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.4; fill:none; animation: cl6-fade .4s ease both }.cl6-eb{ stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:1.8 }.cl6-e1{ animation-delay:1.5s } .cl6-e2{ animation-delay:1.7s } .cl6-e3{ animation-delay:1.9s } .cl6-e4{ animation-delay:2.1s }@keyframes cl6-fade{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.cl6-st{ animation: cl6-pop .4s ease both }.cl6-s0{ animation-delay:1.4s } .cl6-s1{ animation-delay:1.65s } .cl6-s2{ animation-delay:1.85s } .cl6-s3{ animation-delay:2.05s } .cl6-sbad{ animation-delay:2.4s }.cl6-dot{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:1.4 }.cl6-bad{ fill:#fbeee6; stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:2 }.cl6-badx{ stroke:#a3543f; stroke-width:2; stroke-linecap:round }.cl6-note{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic }.cl6-redn{ fill:#a3543f; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600; animation: cl6-fade .5s ease both 2.6s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .cl6 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="cl6"><text class="cl6-title" x="280" y="32">Weak hardware, and proving past it</text><text class="cl6-h" x="280" y="58">memory-model strength &#8212; what reorderings the hardware allows</text><line class="cl6-axis" x1="60" y1="150" x2="500" y2="150"/><rect class="cl6-bar" x="60" y="78" width="440" height="14" rx="7" fill="url(#cl6g)"/><text class="cl6-tk" x="60" y="112" style="text-anchor:start;font-weight:600;fill:#6b7d5c">strong</text><text class="cl6-tk" x="500" y="112" style="text-anchor:end;font-weight:600;fill:#a3543f">weak</text><g class="cl6-chip cl6-c1"><rect class="cl6-chipr" x="60" y="120" width="96" height="42" rx="5"/><text class="cl6-chipt" x="108" y="138">x86 &#183; TSO</text><text class="cl6-chips" x="108" y="154">reorders r-ahead-of-w</text></g><g class="cl6-chip cl6-c2"><rect class="cl6-chipr" x="232" y="120" width="96" height="42" rx="5" style="stroke:#a3543f"/><text class="cl6-chipt" x="280" y="138">ARM</text><text class="cl6-chips" x="280" y="154">reorders freely</text></g><g class="cl6-chip cl6-c3"><rect class="cl6-chipr" x="404" y="120" width="96" height="42" rx="5" style="stroke:#a3543f"/><text class="cl6-chipt" x="452" y="138">Power</text><text class="cl6-chips" x="452" y="154">weakest</text></g><text class="cl6-note" x="280" y="182">code that runs on a laptop can break on a phone</text><text class="cl6-h" x="280" y="212" style="fill:#a3543f">testing can&#8217;t prove it &#8212; a model checker explores every interleaving</text><g><line class="cl6-edge cl6-e1" x1="280" y1="238" x2="190" y2="278"/><line class="cl6-edge cl6-e1" x1="280" y1="238" x2="370" y2="278"/><line class="cl6-edge cl6-e2" x1="190" y1="290" x2="130" y2="326"/><line class="cl6-edge cl6-e2" x1="190" y1="290" x2="250" y2="326"/><line class="cl6-edge cl6-e3" x1="370" y1="290" x2="310" y2="326"/><line class="cl6-edge cl6-eb cl6-e3" x1="370" y1="290" x2="432" y2="326"/></g><g class="cl6-st cl6-s0"><circle class="cl6-dot" cx="280" cy="234" r="11"/></g><g class="cl6-st cl6-s1"><circle class="cl6-dot" cx="190" cy="284" r="10"/></g><g class="cl6-st cl6-s1"><circle class="cl6-dot" cx="370" cy="284" r="10"/></g><g class="cl6-st cl6-s2"><circle class="cl6-dot" cx="130" cy="334" r="10"/></g><g class="cl6-st cl6-s2"><circle class="cl6-dot" cx="250" cy="334" r="10"/></g><g class="cl6-st cl6-s3"><circle class="cl6-dot" cx="310" cy="334" r="10"/></g><g class="cl6-st cl6-sbad"><circle class="cl6-bad" cx="432" cy="334" r="12"/><path class="cl6-badx" d="M427 329 l10 10 M437 329 l-10 10"/></g><text class="cl6-redn" x="432" y="366">violating state</text><text class="cl6-note cl6-st cl6-s2" x="150" y="366">safe interleavings</text><defs><linearGradient id="cl6g" x1="0" y1="0" x2="1" y2="0"><stop offset="0" stop-color="#6b7d5c"/><stop offset="1" stop-color="#a3543f"/></linearGradient></defs></g></svg><figcaption>Hardware ranges from <b>x86&#8217;s</b> strong total-store-order to the weak models of <b>ARM</b> and Power. Since tests cannot prove correctness, a <b>model checker</b> walks every interleaving to hunt the one violating state.</figcaption></figure>`
      }
    ]
  }
