  {
    id: "how-git-works",
    category: "Technology",
    title: "Version Control & How Git Works",
    tagline: "Beneath the everyday commands lies an elegant object store — a tamper-evident graph of every state your work has ever been in.",
    color: "#b0623a",
    glyph: "⎇",
    levels: [
      {
        depth: 1,
        title: "A First Glimpse",
        body: `<p>You know the small dread. You have a document that finally works — the report, the chapter, the program that compiles — and now you want to change it, but changing it might break it. So you make a copy. You name it <code>final</code>. Then you change your mind, and there is <code>final_v2</code>, and then <code>final_v2_REALLY_final</code>, and a week later you are staring at a folder full of near-identical files, unsure which one is the good one.</p><p>Now imagine the same problem with five people editing at once, emailing versions back and forth, each quietly overwriting the others' work. This is the chaos that version control was invented to end.</p><p>Git is the tool that, for most of the world's software, ended it. Think of it as a time machine bolted to your project: at any moment you can step back to exactly how things were last Tuesday, or open a parallel universe where you try a wild idea without endangering the version that works, and then either keep that universe or discard it as if it never happened. Nothing good is ever truly lost.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 330" role="img" aria-label="On the left, the old chaos: a folder full of near-identical files named final, final v2, and final v2 REALLY final, with a worried question of which one is good. An arrow points right to Git's tidy answer: a single line of saved snapshots through time, with a parallel branch where a wild idea can be tried safely and later kept or discarded."><style>.gw1 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.gw1-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; }.gw1-sub{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle }.gw1-file{ animation: gw1-fade .5s ease both; }.gw1-f1{ animation-delay:.15s } .gw1-f2{ animation-delay:.28s } .gw1-f3{ animation-delay:.41s }@keyframes gw1-fade{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateY(6px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateY(0)} }.gw1-paper{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.3 }.gw1-fold{ fill:#d8cdb8 }.gw1-fname{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:10px; text-anchor:middle }.gw1-q{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:13px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw1-fade2 .4s ease both .7s }@keyframes gw1-fade2{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.gw1-arrow{ stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2; fill:none; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:54; stroke-dashoffset:0; animation: gw1-draw .6s ease both .9s }@keyframes gw1-draw{ from{stroke-dashoffset:54} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw1-head{ fill:#b8552e; animation: gw1-fade2 .3s ease both 1.4s }.gw1-line{ stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:2; fill:none; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:170; stroke-dashoffset:0; animation: gw1-draw2 .8s ease both 1.2s }@keyframes gw1-draw2{ from{stroke-dashoffset:170} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw1-branch{ stroke:#6b7d5c; stroke-width:2; fill:none; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:90; stroke-dashoffset:0; animation: gw1-draw3 .7s ease both 1.9s }@keyframes gw1-draw3{ from{stroke-dashoffset:90} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw1-node{ fill:#b8552e; stroke:#1a1410; stroke-width:1.4; transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center; animation: gw1-pop .4s ease both; }.gw1-c1{ animation-delay:1.45s } .gw1-c2{ animation-delay:1.6s } .gw1-c3{ animation-delay:1.75s } .gw1-c4{ animation-delay:1.9s }@keyframes gw1-pop{ from{opacity:0; transform:scale(.3)} to{opacity:1; transform:scale(1)} }.gw1-bnode{ fill:#6b7d5c; stroke:#1a1410; stroke-width:1.4; transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center; animation: gw1-pop .4s ease both; }.gw1-b1{ animation-delay:2.3s } .gw1-b2{ animation-delay:2.45s }.gw1-lab{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.gw1-blab{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw1-fade2 .4s ease both 2.55s }.gw1-note{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw1-fade2 .5s ease both 2.7s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .gw1 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="gw1"><text class="gw1-title" x="280" y="30" text-anchor="middle">From a drawer of copies to one clean history</text><g class="gw1-file gw1-f1"><path class="gw1-paper" d="M40 70 h44 l8 8 v44 h-52 Z"/><path class="gw1-fold" d="M84 70 l8 8 h-8 Z"/><text class="gw1-fname" x="66" y="100">final</text></g><g class="gw1-file gw1-f2"><path class="gw1-paper" d="M64 88 h44 l8 8 v44 h-52 Z"/><path class="gw1-fold" d="M108 88 l8 8 h-8 Z"/><text class="gw1-fname" x="90" y="118">final_v2</text></g><g class="gw1-file gw1-f3"><path class="gw1-paper" d="M88 106 h44 l8 8 v44 h-52 Z"/><path class="gw1-fold" d="M132 106 l8 8 h-8 Z"/><text class="gw1-fname" x="114" y="132">v2_REALLY</text></g><text class="gw1-q" x="95" y="195">which one is good?</text><path class="gw1-arrow" d="M180 130 H236"/><polygon class="gw1-head" points="244,130 232,124 232,136"/><path class="gw1-line" d="M286 130 H520"/><circle class="gw1-node gw1-c1" cx="300" cy="130" r="9"/><circle class="gw1-node gw1-c2" cx="372" cy="130" r="9"/><circle class="gw1-node gw1-c3" cx="444" cy="130" r="9"/><circle class="gw1-node gw1-c4" cx="512" cy="130" r="9"/><path class="gw1-branch" d="M372 130 q24 -34 72 -34"/><circle class="gw1-bnode gw1-b1" cx="444" cy="96" r="9"/><circle class="gw1-bnode gw1-b2" cx="512" cy="96" r="9"/><text class="gw1-lab" x="400" y="168">one history, in order</text><text class="gw1-blab" x="478" y="82">a safe parallel universe</text><text class="gw1-note" x="280" y="300">step back to any moment &#183; branch off to try a wild idea &#183; nothing good is ever lost</text></g></svg><figcaption><b>A time machine for your work.</b> Instead of a drawer of <code>final_v2_REALLY_final</code> copies, Git keeps one ordered history you can step back through &#8212; and lets you open a <b>parallel universe</b> to try an idea, then keep it or discard it as if it never happened.</figcaption></figure><p>And here is the surprise. Git has a reputation for cryptic, intimidating commands. Yet beneath them sits one of the most elegant data structures in all of everyday software — a quiet little machine for remembering.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "A time machine bolted to your project: nothing good is ever truly lost."
      },
      {
        depth: 2,
        title: "Snapshots, Not Differences",
        body: `<p>Most people assume that version control stores <em>changes</em> — that each save records the lines you added and deleted, stacked in a neat chronological pile. It is a reasonable guess, and it is how some older systems worked. Git does something stranger and, in the end, simpler. Git stores <strong>snapshots</strong>. Every time you commit, it conceptually photographs the entire state of your project — every file, every folder — and files that photograph away.</p><p>This sounds wasteful until you learn the second idea, the one that makes the whole thing sing: Git is <strong>content-addressed</strong>. Every object Git stores is named not by you, and not by where it sits, but by a hash of its own contents — a short fingerprint computed from the bytes inside it. Change a single character and the fingerprint changes completely. Keep the bytes identical and the fingerprint is identical, so Git stores that content exactly once, no matter how many snapshots contain it.</p><p>Make that concrete. Take a thousand-file project and commit it; Git writes a blob for each file and a tree for each folder. Now change a single file and commit again. The new commit does <em>not</em> re-store the other 999 files: their bytes are unchanged, so their hashes are unchanged, so the second snapshot simply reuses the 999 blobs already on disk. Git writes only the one new blob and the handful of tree objects along the path from that file up to the root &#8212; often just two or three small lists of names and hashes. So the "whole photograph" is, almost entirely, pointers to bytes Git already had. The snapshot is conceptually complete and physically nearly free.</p><p>From this fall three kinds of object. A <strong>blob</strong> is the contents of a file. A <strong>tree</strong> is a directory: a list of names paired with the hashes of the blobs and trees inside it. A <strong>commit</strong> is a snapshot in time — it points to one tree (the whole project, that instant) plus a note of who made it, when, and why, and crucially a pointer to its <em>parent</em>, the commit that came before.</p><p>String those parent-pointers together and you get the shape that defines Git: a <strong>directed acyclic graph</strong>, a DAG, where history flows from past to present and can fork and rejoin but never loop back on itself. And branches and tags — the things that sound so weighty in tutorials — are revealed to be almost nothing at all: just movable labels, sticky notes pointing at one commit in the graph.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 360" role="img" aria-label="Git's three object types. A blob holds a file's contents and is named by a hash fingerprint of those bytes. A tree is a directory listing names paired with the hashes of the blobs and trees inside it. A commit points to one tree, names an author and message, and points back to its parent commit. Two commits linked parent to child form a directed history that never loops."><style>.gw2 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.gw2-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; }.gw2-sub{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle }.gw2-card{ animation: gw2-fade .5s ease both; }.gw2-blob{ animation-delay:.2s } .gw2-tree{ animation-delay:.55s } .gw2-commit{ animation-delay:.9s }@keyframes gw2-fade{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateY(7px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateY(0)} }.gw2-box{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:1.6 }.gw2-boxb{ fill:#f3e7d2; stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:1.6 }.gw2-boxt{ fill:#eef0e6; stroke:#6b7d5c; stroke-width:1.6 }.gw2-boxc{ fill:#e7eaf0; stroke:#2c3447; stroke-width:1.6 }.gw2-kind{ font-size:13px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.gw2-kb{ fill:#b8552e } .gw2-kt{ fill:#6b7d5c } .gw2-kc{ fill:#2c3447 }.gw2-mono{ font-size:10.5px; text-anchor:middle; fill:#3d322a; font-family: var(--font-mono, monospace) }.gw2-hash{ font-size:10px; text-anchor:middle; fill:#6b5d50; font-family: var(--font-mono, monospace) }.gw2-arrow{ fill:none; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:64; stroke-dashoffset:0 }.gw2-a1{ stroke:#6b7d5c; stroke-width:1.8; animation: gw2-draw .55s ease both 1.3s }.gw2-a2{ stroke:#2c3447; stroke-width:1.8; animation: gw2-draw .55s ease both 1.55s }@keyframes gw2-draw{ from{stroke-dashoffset:64} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw2-h1{ fill:#6b7d5c; animation: gw2-fade2 .3s ease both 1.85s }.gw2-h2{ fill:#2c3447; animation: gw2-fade2 .3s ease both 2.1s }@keyframes gw2-fade2{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.gw2-parent{ fill:none; stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:84; stroke-dashoffset:0; animation: gw2-draw2 .6s ease both 2.3s }@keyframes gw2-draw2{ from{stroke-dashoffset:84} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw2-phead{ fill:#b8552e; animation: gw2-fade2 .3s ease both 2.85s }.gw2-plab{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw2-fade2 .4s ease both 2.9s }.gw2-note{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw2-fade2 .5s ease both 3.0s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .gw2 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="gw2"><text class="gw2-title" x="280" y="30" text-anchor="middle">Three objects, each named by its contents</text><g class="gw2-card gw2-blob"><rect class="gw2-boxb" x="34" y="112" width="132" height="96" rx="7"/><text class="gw2-kind gw2-kb" x="100" y="134">blob</text><text class="gw2-mono" x="100" y="156">file contents</text><text class="gw2-mono" x="100" y="172">(just bytes)</text><text class="gw2-hash" x="100" y="196">e83c5163</text></g><g class="gw2-card gw2-tree"><rect class="gw2-boxt" x="214" y="112" width="132" height="96" rx="7"/><text class="gw2-kind gw2-kt" x="280" y="134">tree</text><text class="gw2-mono" x="280" y="154">main.c &#8594; e83c</text><text class="gw2-mono" x="280" y="170">src/ &#8594; 7c4e</text><text class="gw2-hash" x="280" y="196">a4d1f0b2</text></g><g class="gw2-card gw2-commit"><rect class="gw2-boxc" x="394" y="112" width="132" height="96" rx="7"/><text class="gw2-kind gw2-kc" x="460" y="134">commit</text><text class="gw2-mono" x="460" y="153">tree &#8594; a4d1</text><text class="gw2-mono" x="460" y="169">author, when, why</text><text class="gw2-hash" x="460" y="196">3a9f12c7</text></g><path class="gw2-arrow gw2-a1" d="M166 160 H208"/><polygon class="gw2-h1" points="214,160 204,154 204,166"/><path class="gw2-arrow gw2-a2" d="M346 160 H388"/><polygon class="gw2-h2" points="394,160 384,154 384,166"/><path class="gw2-parent" d="M460 208 v44 h-180"/><polygon class="gw2-phead" points="280,252 287,240 273,240"/><circle cx="280" cy="256" r="7" fill="#e7eaf0" stroke="#2c3447" stroke-width="1.6" class="gw2-h2"/><text class="gw2-plab" x="360" y="272">parent commit</text><text class="gw2-note" x="280" y="316">change one byte &#8594; the fingerprint changes completely; branches are just labels on a commit</text></g></svg><figcaption><b>Snapshots, not differences.</b> A <b>blob</b> is a file's bytes, a <b>tree</b> is a folder listing hashes, a <b>commit</b> is one tree plus a pointer to its parent. Each object is named by a fingerprint of its own contents &#8212; identical bytes are stored exactly once.</figcaption></figure>`,
        pullQuote: "Every object is named by a fingerprint of its own contents."
      },
      {
        depth: 3,
        title: "The Object Model, in Detail",
        body: `<p>Let us open the hood. Inside every Git repository is a hidden folder, <code>.git</code>, and inside it an object database. Everything Git knows about your project's history lives there as those three object types, each stored under the key that <em>is</em> its content's hash.</p><p>A <strong>blob</strong> holds raw file contents and nothing else — no filename, no permissions, no timestamp, just bytes. This is why renaming a file moves no data: the blob is unchanged, so its hash is unchanged, and only the directory listing that mentions it is rewritten.</p><p>A <strong>tree</strong> is that directory listing. Each entry records a mode (file or subdirectory, executable or not), a name, and the hash of the blob or tree it refers to. A project's top-level tree points to subtrees, which point to further subtrees and blobs — a nested structure mirroring your folders exactly.</p><p>A <strong>commit</strong> ties it together. It stores the hash of one tree (the complete snapshot), the hash of its parent commit or commits, the author and committer with timestamps, and your message. Originally Git computed all these hashes with <strong>SHA-1</strong>, producing the familiar 40-character hexadecimal IDs like <code>e83c5163</code>. Because a hash is derived purely from contents, the store is self-verifying: re-hash any object and you can prove it has not been altered.</p><p>Between your files and the next commit sits the <strong>staging area</strong>, also called the <em>index</em> — a draft of the snapshot you are about to take. When you <code>git add</code> a file, you are not saving it forever; you are placing it on the staging table, composing your proposed next photograph. <code>git commit</code> then freezes that proposal into a permanent commit object.</p><p>That this whole model exists at all is a story of urgency. Linus Torvalds wrote the first version of Git in ten days in April 2005, after the Linux kernel community lost access to BitKeeper, the proprietary version-control tool it had relied on. Forced to build a replacement fast, he reached for the spare, content-addressed object store described here.</p><p>The staging area is part of that deliberate design, not an accident. It exists so you can commit a curated subset of your changes &#8212; splitting one messy working state into several clean, logical commits &#8212; rather than being forced to commit everything at once. You stage exactly the lines that belong together, photograph them, then stage the rest for a second, separate commit.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 320" role="img" aria-label="The three places a file lives in Git. On the left, the working directory holds your editable files. The git add command moves a file's snapshot into the middle staging area, also called the index, a draft of the next photograph. The git commit command freezes that draft into a permanent commit object on the right, joining the history."><style>.gw3 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.gw3-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; }.gw3-zone{ animation: gw3-fade .5s ease both; }.gw3-z1{ animation-delay:.15s } .gw3-z2{ animation-delay:.45s } .gw3-z3{ animation-delay:.75s }@keyframes gw3-fade{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateY(7px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateY(0)} }.gw3-panel{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.3; opacity:.9 }.gw3-zlab{ font-size:13px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle; fill:#1a1410 }.gw3-zsub{ font-size:11px; text-anchor:middle; fill:#6b5d50; font-style:italic }.gw3-doc{ fill:#f6ecda; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:1.3 }.gw3-line{ stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2; opacity:.7 }.gw3-line2{ stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.6; opacity:.5 }.gw3-cmt{ fill:#b8552e; stroke:#1a1410; stroke-width:1.5; transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center; animation: gw3-pop .45s ease both 1.15s }@keyframes gw3-pop{ from{opacity:0; transform:scale(.3)} to{opacity:1; transform:scale(1)} }.gw3-cmt2{ fill:#c97b4a; stroke:#1a1410; stroke-width:1.4; opacity:.85; animation: gw3-fade .4s ease both .9s }.gw3-arrow{ fill:none; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:64; stroke-dashoffset:0 }.gw3-aA{ stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2; animation: gw3-draw .55s ease both 1.0s }.gw3-aB{ stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2; animation: gw3-draw .55s ease both 1.5s }@keyframes gw3-draw{ from{stroke-dashoffset:64} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw3-aheadA{ fill:#b8552e; animation: gw3-fade2 .3s ease both 1.4s }.gw3-aheadB{ fill:#b8552e; animation: gw3-fade2 .3s ease both 1.9s }@keyframes gw3-fade2{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.gw3-cmd{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600; font-family: var(--font-mono, monospace) }.gw3-cmdA{ animation: gw3-fade2 .4s ease both 1.2s } .gw3-cmdB{ animation: gw3-fade2 .4s ease both 1.7s }.gw3-note{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw3-fade2 .5s ease both 2.0s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .gw3 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="gw3"><text class="gw3-title" x="280" y="30" text-anchor="middle">add stages a draft, commit freezes it</text><g class="gw3-zone gw3-z1"><rect class="gw3-panel" x="30" y="66" width="150" height="150" rx="8"/><rect class="gw3-doc" x="78" y="104" width="54" height="70" rx="3"/><line class="gw3-line" x1="88" y1="120" x2="122" y2="120"/><line class="gw3-line2" x1="88" y1="134" x2="122" y2="134"/><line class="gw3-line2" x1="88" y1="148" x2="114" y2="148"/><text class="gw3-zlab" x="105" y="244">working directory</text><text class="gw3-zsub" x="105" y="262">your editable files</text></g><g class="gw3-zone gw3-z2"><rect class="gw3-panel" x="205" y="66" width="150" height="150" rx="8"/><rect class="gw3-doc" x="253" y="104" width="54" height="70" rx="3" stroke-dasharray="4 3"/><line class="gw3-line" x1="263" y1="120" x2="297" y2="120"/><line class="gw3-line2" x1="263" y1="134" x2="297" y2="134"/><line class="gw3-line2" x1="263" y1="148" x2="289" y2="148"/><text class="gw3-zlab" x="280" y="244">staging area</text><text class="gw3-zsub" x="280" y="262">the index &#183; a draft snapshot</text></g><g class="gw3-zone gw3-z3"><rect class="gw3-panel" x="380" y="66" width="150" height="150" rx="8"/><circle class="gw3-cmt2" cx="425" cy="140" r="13"/><line class="gw3-line2" x1="438" y1="140" x2="462" y2="140" stroke="#3d322a" opacity=".7"/><circle class="gw3-cmt" cx="480" cy="140" r="15"/><text class="gw3-zlab" x="455" y="244">commit history</text><text class="gw3-zsub" x="455" y="262">permanent objects</text></g><path class="gw3-arrow gw3-aA" d="M184 130 H201"/><polygon class="gw3-aheadA" points="205,130 196,124 196,136"/><path class="gw3-arrow gw3-aB" d="M359 130 H376"/><polygon class="gw3-aheadB" points="380,130 371,124 371,136"/><text class="gw3-cmd gw3-cmdA" x="192" y="100">git add</text><text class="gw3-cmd gw3-cmdB" x="369" y="100">git commit</text><text class="gw3-note" x="280" y="300">branch = a movable label on a commit &#183; merge = a commit with two parents</text></g></svg><figcaption><b>The staging table.</b> <code>git add</code> lays a file's snapshot on the <b>index</b> &#8212; a draft of the photograph you are about to take &#8212; and <code>git commit</code> freezes that draft into a permanent commit object that joins the history.</figcaption></figure><p>With that picture, the everyday verbs lose their mystery. To <strong>commit</strong> is to write a new commit object pointing at the current parent and a fresh tree. To create a <strong>branch</strong> is to write a new movable label pointing at a commit — a single line in a file, nothing more. To <strong>merge</strong> two branches is to make a new commit with <em>two</em> parents, knitting two lines of history into one. To <strong>rebase</strong> is to lift a sequence of commits off one base and replant them atop another, rewriting them as you go. Every operation, underneath, is a small surgery on the graph.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 4,
        title: "Merkle Trees and the Architecture of Trust",
        body: `<p>Content-addressing is not merely a clever filing scheme. It is the doorway to a deeper structure, and understanding that structure explains why Git can be trusted to guard years of work.</p><p>Because a tree object contains the <em>hashes</em> of its children, and a commit contains the hash of its tree and of its parent, the hashes are chained all the way down. This arrangement has a name: a <strong>Merkle tree</strong>, after Ralph Merkle, who patented the idea in 1979 — more precisely a <strong>Merkle DAG</strong>, since history branches and rejoins. The defining property is transitivity. A node's hash depends on its contents, which include the hashes of its children, which depend on <em>their</em> children, and so on to the leaves. So the hash at the top covers everything beneath it.</p><p>Follow the consequence. A commit's hash is computed from its tree and its parent's hash. Its parent's hash was computed from <em>that</em> commit's tree and <em>its</em> parent — and so on back to the very first commit. Therefore a single commit ID is a <strong>cryptographic fingerprint of its entire ancestry</strong>: every file in every snapshot that ever led to this moment. Alter one byte in one file in one ancient commit, and that commit's hash changes, which changes its child's hash, which cascades all the way to the present. Tampering cannot hide; it announces itself by breaking the chain. The store is, in the proper sense, <em>tamper-evident</em>.<figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 372" role="img" aria-label="A Merkle DAG. Three commits chained left to right, each commit's hash computed from its tree and its parent's hash, so a single commit ID fingerprints its entire ancestry. Altering one byte in the oldest tree recomputes that object's hash, which cascades forward and changes every descendant commit's hash, so tampering breaks the chain and announces itself."><style>.gw4 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.gw4-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; }.gw4-sub{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle }.gw4-node{ animation: gw4-pop .45s ease both; }.gw4-cA{ animation-delay:.2s } .gw4-cB{ animation-delay:.45s } .gw4-cC{ animation-delay:.7s }@keyframes gw4-pop{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateY(6px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateY(0)} }.gw4-cbox{ fill:#e7eaf0; stroke:#2c3447; stroke-width:1.6 }.gw4-clab{ fill:#2c3447; font-size:11.5px; font-weight:600; text-anchor:middle }.gw4-chash{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:10.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-family: var(--font-mono, monospace) }.gw4-oldhash{ opacity:0; animation: gw4-vanish .3s ease both; }.gw4-oA{ animation-delay:2.0s } .gw4-oB{ animation-delay:2.35s } .gw4-oC{ animation-delay:2.7s }@keyframes gw4-vanish{ from{opacity:1} to{opacity:0} }.gw4-leaf{ fill:#eef0e6; stroke:#6b7d5c; stroke-width:1.4; }.gw4-leaftamper{ fill:#f3e7d2; stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:1.8; }.gw4-leaflab{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:10.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-family: var(--font-mono, monospace) }.gw4-chain{ fill:none; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:2; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:48; stroke-dashoffset:0 }.gw4-ch1{ animation: gw4-draw .5s ease both .9s } .gw4-ch2{ animation: gw4-draw .5s ease both 1.1s }@keyframes gw4-draw{ from{stroke-dashoffset:48} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw4-chead{ fill:#3d322a; }.gw4-h1{ animation: gw4-fade .3s ease both 1.3s } .gw4-h2{ animation: gw4-fade .3s ease both 1.5s }@keyframes gw4-fade{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.gw4-up{ fill:none; stroke:#6b7d5c; stroke-width:1.4; opacity:.7; stroke-dasharray:40; stroke-dashoffset:0; animation: gw4-draw2 .5s ease both 1.0s }@keyframes gw4-draw2{ from{stroke-dashoffset:40} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw4-tamperlab{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:11px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600; animation: gw4-fade .4s ease both 2.0s }.gw4-redhash{ fill:#b8552e; font-weight:600; opacity:1; animation: gw4-fade .45s ease both; }.gw4-rA{ animation-delay:2.0s } .gw4-rB{ animation-delay:2.35s } .gw4-rC{ animation-delay:2.7s }.gw4-cascade{ fill:none; stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2.4; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:6 7; }.gw4-csc1{ stroke-dashoffset:0; animation: gw4-draw3 .5s ease both 2.2s }.gw4-csc2{ stroke-dashoffset:0; animation: gw4-draw3 .5s ease both 2.55s }@keyframes gw4-draw3{ from{stroke-dashoffset:80} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw4-cshead{ fill:#b8552e; }.gw4-csh1{ animation: gw4-fade .3s ease both 2.7s } .gw4-csh2{ animation: gw4-fade .3s ease both 3.05s }.gw4-note{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; font-weight:600; animation: gw4-fade .5s ease both 3.2s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .gw4 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="gw4"><text class="gw4-title" x="280" y="30" text-anchor="middle">A commit ID fingerprints its whole ancestry</text><text class="gw4-sub" x="280" y="50">each hash is built from its tree and its parent's hash &#183; a Merkle DAG</text><path class="gw4-up" d="M96 204 V172"/><path class="gw4-up" d="M280 204 V172"/><path class="gw4-up" d="M464 204 V172"/><path class="gw4-chain gw4-ch1" d="M152 143 H220"/><polygon class="gw4-chead gw4-h1" points="224,143 214,137 214,149"/><path class="gw4-chain gw4-ch2" d="M336 143 H404"/><polygon class="gw4-chead gw4-h2" points="408,143 398,137 398,149"/><g class="gw4-node gw4-cA"><rect class="gw4-cbox" x="40" y="116" width="112" height="54" rx="6"/><text class="gw4-clab" x="96" y="138">commit A</text><text class="gw4-chash gw4-oldhash gw4-oA" x="96" y="157">e83c5163</text><text class="gw4-chash gw4-redhash gw4-rA" x="96" y="157">1b7f00a2</text><rect class="gw4-leaftamper" x="56" y="204" width="80" height="30" rx="4"/><text class="gw4-leaflab" x="96" y="223" fill="#b8552e">tree 7c4e</text></g><g class="gw4-node gw4-cB"><rect class="gw4-cbox" x="224" y="116" width="112" height="54" rx="6"/><text class="gw4-clab" x="280" y="138">commit B</text><text class="gw4-chash gw4-oldhash gw4-oB" x="280" y="157">3a9f12c7</text><text class="gw4-chash gw4-redhash gw4-rB" x="280" y="157">c2e8d410</text><rect class="gw4-leaf" x="240" y="204" width="80" height="30" rx="4"/><text class="gw4-leaflab" x="280" y="223">tree b1d0</text></g><g class="gw4-node gw4-cC"><rect class="gw4-cbox" x="408" y="116" width="112" height="54" rx="6"/><text class="gw4-clab" x="464" y="138">commit C</text><text class="gw4-chash gw4-oldhash gw4-oC" x="464" y="157">9f4ada21</text><text class="gw4-chash gw4-redhash gw4-rC" x="464" y="157">7e0b93f5</text><rect class="gw4-leaf" x="424" y="204" width="80" height="30" rx="4"/><text class="gw4-leaflab" x="464" y="223">tree c5e8</text></g><path class="gw4-cascade gw4-csc1" d="M152 143 H220"/><polygon class="gw4-cshead gw4-csh1" points="224,143 214,137 214,149"/><path class="gw4-cascade gw4-csc2" d="M336 143 H404"/><polygon class="gw4-cshead gw4-csh2" points="408,143 398,137 398,149"/><text class="gw4-tamperlab" x="96" y="264">alter one ancient byte</text><text class="gw4-tamperlab" x="96" y="280" font-weight="400" font-style="italic">the tree's hash changes</text><text class="gw4-note" x="316" y="272">&#8230;and every descendant commit's hash<tspan x="316" dy="17">changes too &#8212; tampering cannot hide</tspan></text></g></svg><figcaption><b>Tamper-evident by construction.</b> Because each commit's hash is built from its tree and its parent's hash, a single ID is a cryptographic fingerprint of its entire ancestry. Alter one byte in one old file and the change <b>cascades all the way to the present</b>, breaking the chain.</figcaption></figure></p><p>This is the same idea that secures very different systems. A blockchain such as Bitcoin is a Merkle-chained ledger whose every block fingerprints its predecessor. The peer-to-peer file system <strong>IPFS</strong> addresses all content by hash in a Merkle DAG, so that a name guarantees its data. Git arrived at the structure first, in 2005, for the humbler purpose of remembering source code.</p><p>Two further principles complete the design. The object store is <strong>append-only and immutable</strong>: objects are written once and never modified in place. What looks like editing history — amending a commit, rebasing — does not alter old objects; it creates <em>new</em> ones with new hashes and merely points the labels elsewhere, leaving the originals untouched until garbage collection eventually reclaims the unreferenced ones. And Git is <strong>distributed by design</strong>. When you clone a repository you receive not a thin checkout but the entire object database — every commit, every version, the whole Merkle DAG. There is no privileged central copy in the model itself; GitHub is a convention, not a requirement. Every clone is a full, self-sufficient repository, which is precisely why work survives outages, lost laptops, and abandoned servers.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 5,
        title: "Merges, Packfiles, and Reading Raw Objects",
        body: `<p>Now the machinery in earnest. When you merge two branches that have genuinely diverged, Git performs a <strong>three-way merge</strong>. The three inputs are the two branch tips and their <strong>merge base</strong> — the most recent commit that is an ancestor of both, the lowest common ancestor in the DAG. Git compares each tip against that base: a hunk changed on only one side is taken automatically; a hunk changed on both sides, differently, is a <strong>conflict</strong>, which Git marks with <code>&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;</code>, <code>=======</code>, <code>&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</code> markers and asks you to resolve. The result becomes a merge commit with two parents.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 360" role="img" aria-label="A three-way merge. From a common merge base commit, history forks into two branch tips, ours and theirs. Git compares each tip against the base: a hunk changed on only one side is taken automatically, while a hunk changed on both sides differently becomes a conflict. The two tips are then joined into a single merge commit that has two parents."><style>.gw5 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.gw5-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; }.gw5-sub{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle }.gw5-edge{ fill:none; stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:2; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:120; stroke-dashoffset:0 }.gw5-e1{ animation: gw5-draw .55s ease both .55s } .gw5-e2{ animation: gw5-draw .55s ease both .7s }.gw5-e3{ stroke:#b8552e; animation: gw5-draw .55s ease both 1.7s } .gw5-e4{ stroke:#b8552e; animation: gw5-draw .55s ease both 1.85s }@keyframes gw5-draw{ from{stroke-dashoffset:120} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw5-node{ stroke:#1a1410; stroke-width:1.6; transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center; animation: gw5-pop .45s ease both; }.gw5-base{ fill:#b8923a; animation-delay:.2s }.gw5-ours{ fill:#6b7d5c; animation-delay:.95s }.gw5-theirs{ fill:#2c3447; animation-delay:1.1s }.gw5-merge{ fill:#b8552e; animation-delay:2.4s }@keyframes gw5-pop{ from{opacity:0; transform:scale(.3)} to{opacity:1; transform:scale(1)} }.gw5-nlab{ font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600 }.gw5-lbase{ fill:#9a7a2e } .gw5-lours{ fill:#5a6b4c } .gw5-ltheirs{ fill:#2c3447 } .gw5-lmerge{ fill:#b8552e }.gw5-auto{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw5-fade .4s ease both 1.5s }@keyframes gw5-fade{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.gw5-conf{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:11.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600; animation: gw5-fade .4s ease both 1.55s }.gw5-confbox{ fill:#b8552e; opacity:.12; animation: gw5-fade .4s ease both 1.45s }.gw5-mlab{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw5-fade .5s ease both 2.7s }.gw5-note{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw5-fade .5s ease both 2.85s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .gw5 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="gw5"><text class="gw5-title" x="280" y="30" text-anchor="middle">A three-way merge joins two histories</text><text class="gw5-sub" x="280" y="50">compare each tip against their common merge base</text><path class="gw5-edge gw5-e1" d="M96 200 Q170 130 244 118"/><path class="gw5-edge gw5-e2" d="M96 200 Q170 270 244 282"/><path class="gw5-edge gw5-e3" d="M300 118 Q380 130 452 196"/><path class="gw5-edge gw5-e4" d="M300 282 Q380 270 452 204"/><circle class="gw5-node gw5-base" cx="96" cy="200" r="17"/><circle class="gw5-node gw5-ours" cx="272" cy="118" r="15"/><circle class="gw5-node gw5-theirs" cx="272" cy="282" r="15"/><circle class="gw5-node gw5-merge" cx="464" cy="200" r="17"/><text class="gw5-nlab gw5-lbase" x="96" y="244">merge base</text><text class="gw5-sub" x="96" y="262">common ancestor</text><text class="gw5-nlab gw5-lours" x="272" y="96">ours</text><text class="gw5-nlab gw5-ltheirs" x="272" y="314">theirs</text><text class="gw5-nlab gw5-lmerge" x="464" y="244">merge commit</text><text class="gw5-sub" x="464" y="262">two parents</text><rect class="gw5-confbox" x="330" y="168" width="96" height="24" rx="4"/><text class="gw5-auto" x="380" y="150">one side changed &#8594; taken</text><text class="gw5-conf" x="380" y="184">both changed &#8594; conflict</text><text class="gw5-mlab" x="280" y="338">fast-forward skips this when one branch is merely ahead</text></g></svg><figcaption><b>Three-way, not two.</b> Git diffs both tips against their <b>merge base</b> &#8212; the lowest common ancestor. A hunk changed on one side is taken automatically; changed on both sides, it is a <b>conflict</b> you resolve. The result is a commit with two parents.</figcaption></figure><p>If one branch is simply ahead of the other — the base <em>is</em> the older tip — there is nothing to reconcile, and Git performs a <strong>fast-forward</strong>: it slides the label forward with no new commit at all. A <strong>rebase</strong>, by contrast, takes your commits, computes the patch each one introduced, and <em>replays</em> them one by one onto a new base. Because each replayed commit now has a different parent (and possibly different content), it is a brand-new object with a brand-new hash. This is the heart of the warning never to rebase shared history: you are not moving commits, you are manufacturing impostors and orphaning the originals.</p><p>For storage, Git would be profligate if it kept every snapshot whole. So it periodically writes <strong>packfiles</strong>, in which similar objects are stored as <em>deltas</em> — one object recorded in full, others as compact instructions for transforming it — and the whole pack is zlib-compressed. Delta compression is chosen heuristically across the repository, not tied to commit order, which is why a large history can collapse to a remarkably small <code>.git</code> directory.</p><p>A <strong>delta</strong> is not a line diff but a byte-level recipe: a short program of two instructions &#8212; <em>copy</em> a run of bytes from a chosen base object, and <em>insert</em> new literal bytes &#8212; that reconstructs one object from another. To pick the base, Git's packer sorts candidate objects by type, then by path name, then by descending size, so that objects likely to resemble each other sit near one another. It then walks a sliding <strong>window</strong> of recent candidates (ten by default) and tries to deltify each object against them, keeping whichever yields the smallest delta. Bases may themselves be deltas, so chains form, capped by a maximum <code>--depth</code> (fifty by default) to bound reconstruction cost. Crucially, this similarity search ignores commit order entirely.</p><p>The payoff is not subtle. Because Git records each near-identical version as a compact delta against a chosen base rather than as a whole snapshot, the first <code>git gc</code> on a young repository routinely shrinks its sprawl of loose objects by roughly an order of magnitude &#8212; a directory of redundant copies collapsing toward a tenth its size. At the extreme, the Linux kernel's history &#8212; more than a million commits across two decades &#8212; packs into a <code>.git</code> directory of only a few gigabytes, a fraction of what storing even one uncompressed checkout per revision would demand.</p><p>Safety lives in the <strong>reflog</strong>. Every time a label like <code>HEAD</code> or a branch moves, Git records the previous position in a local log. So even after a reckless <code>reset --hard</code> or a botched rebase, the supposedly lost commits are still in the object store, and <code>git reflog</code> will show you the hash to recover them. <strong>HEAD</strong> itself is just a pointer to your current branch; check out a raw commit instead of a branch and you enter <strong>detached HEAD</strong> — working atop a commit no label is tracking, where new commits risk being garbage-collected unless you name them.</p><p>You can see all of this directly. Git ships a "plumbing" command, <code>git cat-file</code>, that reads the raw store:</p><pre>$ git cat-file -t e83c5163      # what type is this object?
commit
$ git cat-file -p e83c5163      # print its contents
tree 7c4e8b...
parent 3a9f12...
author Ada Lovelace &lt;ada@example.com&gt; 1748736000 +0000
committer Ada Lovelace &lt;ada@example.com&gt; 1748736000 +0000

Fix the off-by-one in the carriage loop</pre><p>Print the tree it names and you get a directory listing of names and hashes; print one of those blob hashes and you get a file's exact contents. You can even compute an object's name yourself: Git hashes the bytes <code>"blob " + length + "\\0" + contents</code>. There is no hidden magic — only hashes, all the way down.</p>`
      },
      {
        depth: 6,
        title: "Collisions, Monorepos, and the Frontier of Versioning",
        body: `<p>Content-addressing rests on one assumption: that two different things never share a hash. For SHA-1 that assumption frayed. Cryptographers had warned for years that SHA-1 was weakening, and in February 2017 a team at Google and CWI Amsterdam announced <strong>SHAttered</strong> — the first practical SHA-1 collision, two distinct PDF files with the same digest, produced with enormous but feasible computation. For a content-addressed store this is existential: if an attacker can craft two objects with the same name, the guarantee that a hash uniquely identifies its contents collapses, and tamper-evidence with it. Git's exposure was limited (it added a collision-detecting variant of SHA-1, and its object framing differs from a raw PDF), but the writing was on the wall. The project has since defined a parallel object format using <strong>SHA-256</strong>, with interoperability between the two hash worlds an ongoing engineering effort led by maintainer <strong>Junio Hamano</strong> and contributors such as Brian Carlson. The episode is a clean lesson in what <em>collision resistance</em> actually buys an integrity system, and how a foundational primitive can age out from under a design.</p><figure class="lsn-fig"><svg class="lsn-dia" viewBox="0 0 560 350" role="img" aria-label="The SHAttered collision. Two different input files are fed into the SHA-1 hash function and, against the founding assumption of content-addressing, both produce the exact same digest. Because a content-addressed store assumes one hash means one unique content, a collision lets two distinct objects share a name and breaks tamper-evidence. The fix is to move to the stronger SHA-256 hash."><style>.gw6 text{ font-family: var(--font-body); }.gw6-title{ fill:#1a1410; font-size:18px; font-weight:600; }.gw6-sub{ fill:#6b5d50; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle }.gw6-doc{ animation: gw6-fade .5s ease both; }.gw6-d1{ animation-delay:.2s } .gw6-d2{ animation-delay:.4s }@keyframes gw6-fade{ from{opacity:0; transform:translateX(-6px)} to{opacity:1; transform:translateX(0)} }.gw6-paper{ fill:#efe6d4; stroke:#3d322a; stroke-width:1.4 }.gw6-fold{ fill:#d8cdb8 }.gw6-dl{ stroke:#2c3447; stroke-width:1.6; opacity:.6 }.gw6-dl2{ stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:1.6; opacity:.6 }.gw6-dlab{ fill:#3d322a; font-size:11px; text-anchor:middle }.gw6-arrow{ fill:none; stroke:#6b5d50; stroke-width:1.8; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:70; stroke-dashoffset:0 }.gw6-a1{ animation: gw6-draw .55s ease both .8s } .gw6-a2{ animation: gw6-draw .55s ease both 1.0s }@keyframes gw6-draw{ from{stroke-dashoffset:70} to{stroke-dashoffset:0} }.gw6-ahead{ fill:#6b5d50; animation: gw6-fade2 .3s ease both 1.3s }@keyframes gw6-fade2{ from{opacity:0} to{opacity:1} }.gw6-fn{ fill:#2c3447; stroke:#2c3447; stroke-width:1.6; animation: gw6-fade2 .5s ease both 1.2s }.gw6-fnlab{ fill:#f4ede0; font-size:14px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600; animation: gw6-fade2 .5s ease both 1.4s }.gw6-collide{ fill:none; stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2; stroke-linecap:round; stroke-dasharray:60; stroke-dashoffset:0; animation: gw6-draw .5s ease both 1.7s }.gw6-chead{ fill:#b8552e; animation: gw6-fade2 .3s ease both 2.0s }.gw6-digest{ fill:#f3e7d2; stroke:#b8552e; stroke-width:2; animation: gw6-pop .5s ease both 2.1s }@keyframes gw6-pop{ from{opacity:0; transform:scale(.6)} to{opacity:1; transform:scale(1)} transform-box:fill-box; transform-origin:center }.gw6-dghash{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:12px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600; font-family: var(--font-mono, monospace); animation: gw6-fade2 .4s ease both 2.35s }.gw6-bang{ fill:#b8552e; font-size:13px; text-anchor:middle; font-weight:600; font-style:italic; animation: gw6-fade2 .4s ease both 2.5s }.gw6-fix{ fill:#6b7d5c; font-size:12.5px; text-anchor:middle; font-style:italic; animation: gw6-fade2 .5s ease both 2.75s }@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce){ .gw6 *{ animation:none!important } }</style><g class="gw6"><text class="gw6-title" x="280" y="30" text-anchor="middle">SHAttered: two files, one hash</text><text class="gw6-sub" x="280" y="50">the founding assumption &#8212; one hash, one content &#8212; cracks</text><g class="gw6-doc gw6-d1"><path class="gw6-paper" d="M40 86 h56 l12 12 v66 h-68 Z"/><path class="gw6-fold" d="M96 86 l12 12 h-12 Z"/><line class="gw6-dl" x1="52" y1="112" x2="96" y2="112"/><line class="gw6-dl" x1="52" y1="128" x2="96" y2="128"/><line class="gw6-dl" x1="52" y1="144" x2="88" y2="144"/><text class="gw6-dlab" x="74" y="180">file A</text></g><g class="gw6-doc gw6-d2"><path class="gw6-paper" d="M40 196 h56 l12 12 v66 h-68 Z"/><path class="gw6-fold" d="M96 196 l12 12 h-12 Z"/><line class="gw6-dl2" x1="52" y1="222" x2="96" y2="222"/><line class="gw6-dl2" x1="52" y1="238" x2="96" y2="238"/><line class="gw6-dl2" x1="52" y1="254" x2="88" y2="254"/><text class="gw6-dlab" x="74" y="290">file B (different)</text></g><path class="gw6-arrow gw6-a1" d="M118 130 Q170 150 214 178"/><polygon class="gw6-ahead" points="220,182 208,178 213,170"/><path class="gw6-arrow gw6-a2" d="M118 230 Q170 210 214 184"/><polygon class="gw6-ahead" points="220,180 208,184 213,192"/><rect class="gw6-fn" x="224" y="160" width="108" height="44" rx="8"/><text class="gw6-fnlab" x="278" y="187">SHA-1</text><path class="gw6-collide" d="M332 182 H392"/><polygon class="gw6-chead" points="398,182 386,176 386,188"/><rect class="gw6-digest" x="402" y="160" width="128" height="44" rx="8"/><text class="gw6-dghash" x="466" y="187">38762cf7&#8230;</text><text class="gw6-bang" x="466" y="230">the same digest!</text><text class="gw6-fix" x="280" y="322">a collision lets two objects share a name &#8212; the fix: move to SHA-256</text></g></svg><figcaption><b>When a hash stops being unique.</b> In 2017 SHAttered forged two distinct files with the same SHA-1 digest. For a content-addressed store that is existential: if two objects can share a name, the guarantee collapses &#8212; which is why Git is moving toward <b>SHA-256</b>.</figcaption></figure><p>The other great pressure is <strong>scale</strong>. Git was built for the Linux kernel — large, but text. Companies like Microsoft, Google, and Meta run <strong>monorepos</strong> with millions of files and decades of history, where a naive clone would download tens of gigabytes nobody needs. The answers reshape Git's assumption that every clone is the whole repository. <strong>Shallow clones</strong> fetch only recent history; <strong>partial clones</strong> defer downloading blobs until they are actually read; <strong>sparse checkout</strong> populates only the directories you work in. Microsoft built <strong>VFS for Git</strong> (originally GVFS), virtualizing the working tree so files materialize on access, and later <strong>Scalar</strong>, much of which has been folded back into mainline Git. The model bends toward "a full repository in principle, lazily realized in practice."</p><p>Git did not end the conversation about how version control <em>should</em> work. <strong>Mercurial</strong>, born the same month as Git in 2005, made nearly the same choices with a gentler interface. <strong>Fossil</strong>, written by SQLite's D. Richard Hipp, bundles a wiki and bug tracker into the repository itself. Most intriguing is <strong>Pijul</strong>, which abandons the snapshot-and-replay model for a rigorous <em>theory of patches</em> grounded in category theory, aiming to make merges associative and commutative — so that the order in which changes arrive cannot change the result, a property Git's three-way merge does not guarantee. Darcs pioneered this patch-theoretic path before it; Pijul tries to make it fast.</p><p>The reason Git cannot promise this is structural. A three-way merge reconstructs its answer from exactly three commits &#8212; the two tips and their single merge base &#8212; and discards every intermediate step that produced them. When history forks and rejoins more than once, this becomes the notorious <strong>criss-cross merge</strong>: two branches that have each already merged the other share two candidate ancestors, not one, and which base Git picks can flip a clean auto-merge into a conflict, or yield different resolved text. Merge the same commits in a different order and you can land in a different state. Pijul instead records each change as a patch carrying its explicit dependencies, so applying the same set of patches in any order provably reaches the identical result &#8212; commutativity by construction, not by luck of the graph.</p><p>Open questions remain genuinely open. Merge algorithms still operate on lines of text and stumble on moved code, refactors, and structured data; <em>syntactic</em> and <em>semantic</em> merge tools are an active research area. Real conflict-free collaboration on shared documents is handled today by CRDTs in editors, not by Git. And version control for <strong>non-text artifacts</strong> — images, datasets, 3D models, machine-learning model weights — remains awkward, served by bolt-ons like Git LFS and separate systems like DVC rather than by the object store itself. <strong>Linus Torvalds</strong> wrote the first Git in ten days in April 2005, after the kernel community lost access to the proprietary tool BitKeeper, then handed the project to Hamano, who has shepherded it ever since. Two decades on, the little machine for remembering is nearly universal — and still, quietly, unfinished.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "Only hashes, all the way down — until the day a hash is no longer unique."
      }
    ]
  }
